I get to work at my dream property this upcoming week and I’m beyond stoked. It’s a massive honor and opportunity and exactly why I came to LA. I’ve always pushed myself professionally to try to be the best I can, never not working, always here to help. It’s an incredible feeling trusting in the universes plan and my intuition when I’ve given something my all and it no longer serves me. Having faith that the next step will work out or be even better because I’ve worked for it, I’ve aligned myself with it. I definitely fuck up a lot and have a lot of habits I still work on, but I’m always trying and improving. I just felt like sharing this rant because I’m blown away but what I’ve been able to achieve within only a few years. My professional success has had a profound impact on my mental health and vice versa, for the better. I’m not saying all this to brag but more so (if you’re still reading) to urge you to take the chance (ofc make some calculated decisions with it) and do it already if you’re unhappy with life.

What does brainwashing mean to you? To me, it makes me think of all of the conscious and unconscious conditioning we experience in life. How systems and companies are built by creating dichotomies between people or a feeling of lack or scarcity. - or just legitimate scarcity such as housing, food, and job resources. We are a free country yet have one of the highest rates of incarceration, we have fair housing yet there are no rent caps on the newest buildings and with the trickle down effect apartments are causing gentrification of urban areas without providing comparable options for low income or affordable housing. 

We have enough food to feed the world, but yet we don’t. We have enough water to satiate the thirsty, yet we don’t. It’s not a lack of resources it’s an issue of self idolatry instead of conflating opinions. It’s ego versus the whole and what’s so sad is we all talk about it, we all joke how everything is doomed and the worlds economy, and ecology is struggling. We give excuses as to why we don’t solve world problems and there seems to be an air of resignation. That it’s just how things are. 

Throughout history there have been cycles of war and enlightenment, economic turbulence and surges, the great dust bowl etc. but I think we are increasingly seeing a shortening period between for example market crashes, extreme weather, and extreme poverty. It’s not very elusive why these issues aren’t being resolved- it’s because our attention is in the product. Brands, apps, our attention is money and so large companies pump trillions of dollars into learning how to keep and maintain your attention instead of you using it to figure out how to give back. This type of mass populous control has been happening for centuries but is even more prevalent now due to the invasiveness of social media. We are social animals by nature, and so many people I hear, claim to be enlightened, and yet all they do is perpetuate the system. Thanks for listening to this rant. I’m just curious about ways that we can actually make a difference instead of being resigned to the world that we know is failing in a lot of ways.

Are you willing to pay the price?

About a year ago, I dropped to my knees, touched my head to the floorand I prayed to the universe that I was willing to take on whatever it took to get me where I needed to be and that I was so grateful for the challenges and pain I had already gone through to get to the place that I wanted to be at and to achieve the goals I had already achieved. I felt humiliated doing it, but it felt right. I was scared to almost challenge the universe to throw it at me and I still get upset at times and impatient, but I also have the awareness to see the beauty and to see the lessons that are limiting me from the potentials I want to reach. I plan to listen to this on, repeat every day of my life @hormozi  because every new level that I achieve I always have new struggles to encounter and it does take the confidence and awareness of the larger picture and that there is no growth without pain, but that pain is beautiful. At the same time I would like to urge that when you’re actually in the pain and in that moment, it is not fucking easy and words seem very small action is what matters.

Today’s training was awesome. Budgets for businesses are fascinating and complex but also they have consistent frameworks that make them comprehensible and replicable. I’m grateful for the opportunities I’m experiencing and the exposure to knowledge from experts in their fields.

Hi 🙃, my names McKynzie. I’m in luxury property management and am also developing my own marketing company. @thecollectionsofus will primarily be focused around mental health awareness, financial and professional efficacy, and more. 

Come check out my page if your curious, I’ve used these techniques to earn 1-2 promotions a year for the last several years. I have moved from my college town all the way to Hollywood following these mentalities and thought processes and I’m excited to share.

Got to attend a film industry night where @lawrencesherdp spoke as well as some other incredible cinematographers and colorists. It was genuinely a reflective experience, hearing how so many people you admire; made it where they are. The creative eye fascinated me because although technique can be trained, someone’s inclination for beauty is personal and relative. What’s popular generally has symmetry or triggers a biological response that some are more attuned to than others. It’s beautiful ❤️

I’m curious, do you get that feeling in the pit of your stomach? Like there’s more out there for you? This year has been incredible and as of October 22nd ill be coming up on my first year in Hollywood. I’ve stayed on track with one promotion during the course of the year here and look forward to another one within the next few months 🤞

This whole art installation was about resurrection, beauty in the things we often take for granted, and realignment of intention and purpose.

The feedback I hear a lot from not only my residents but the world around me is that the world has gone mad. I think so to, but I think it also already was. If you reflect on the fact that there have always been cycles of turbulence in between periods of exceptional intrapersonal/societal growth- the renaissance, the great enlightenment, etc. you’ll notice that the chaos around us is a reflection of the ever growing push for change. Change in the way we as humans are being perceived and restricted in terms of societal norms and practices. What was once pushed into the masses as healthy has now been proven cancerous (you could insert many things here). 

I use to get wrapped up in fear mongering, but I’ve come to realize and embolden myself in the art of letting go of what is out of my control and prioritizing what is in my control in order to be effective overall. What I’m trying to relay is that, ya the world might be burning but to me that simply means that we as humans need to embody the change we want to see first and foremost.
